@Mikus180AD Yes! Easiest way to get on a professors good side. It wasn’t intentional for me tho. I just happened to be dealing with undiagnosed adhd and figured out the only way I could focus in class was by sitting in the front row and actively participating

This weekend was a 3 day weekend for me and I chose to unplug 100% from work related tasks. I felt so much more equipped to take on my week this morning, but that also meant I had to let a few items slip through the cracks🤷‍♀️
Basically it’s a vicious cycle and I’m perpetually burnt out OR I have to let things fall through the cracks so I can recharge.

So I can never just “relax” because I always need to plan ahead. This, coupled with the extra brainpower it requires for me to stay on task (meds help, but effort is still required) means I burn out quicker than a neurotypical person, which means I need more downtime.

The problem is, the responsible adult is also the child who struggles with executive dysfunction. So planning and executing are difficult to begin with, but NEED to happen ahead of time or else everything falls apart. (Literally and figuratively)

The best way I can describe living with adhd as an adult is simultaneously performing the roles of parent and child but you’re both the parent and the child. The child cannot focus or provide structure, so as the adult, I have to provide that for myself.
